  "description": "Live detection dashboard for the DeSFAM ML inference engine. Monitors per-process syscall sequences streamed from eBPF (Tetragon) and scores them with an Isolation Forest + VAE ensemble. Threshold derived from validation-set percentile; scores above it trigger alerts.",
  "editable": true,
  "fiscalYearStartMonth": 0,
  "graphTooltip": 1,
  "id": null,
  "links": [],
  "panels": [
    {
      "id": 200,
      "type": "row",
      "title": "Guide \u2014 How to read this dashboard (click to expand)",
      "collapsed": true,
      "gridPos": {
        "y": 0,
        "x": 0,
        "h": 1,
        "w": 24
      },
      "panels": [
        {
          "id": 100,
          "type": "text",
          "title": "",
          "gridPos": {
            "y": 1,
            "x": 0,
            "h": 13,
            "w": 24
          },
          "options": {
            "mode": "markdown",
            "content": "## DeSFAM \u2014 Syscall Anomaly Detection Dashboard\n\n**How scoring works:** Tetragon (eBPF) captures every syscall made by each container. When a process exits, its full syscall trace is scored by two models and combined into one ensemble score.\n\n| Component | What it measures | High score means |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Isolation Forest (IF)** | Unusual syscall *frequency* \u2014 anomalies isolated in fewer tree splits | Call frequencies are far from normal |\n| **VAE (Autoencoder)** | Unusual syscall *sequence patterns* \u2014 trained on normal traces only | Sequence structure doesn't match normal behavior |\n| **Ensemble** | `0.7 \u00d7 RobustScaled(VAE error) + 0.3 \u00d7 RobustScaled(IF score)` | Combined anomaly signal |\n\n**Why scores can be negative:** Both scalers are centred on the *median* of normal training scores, so a typical normal trace scores near 0. Traces scoring below 0 are more-normal-than-average.\n\n**Threshold (0.08):** The model was trained on DongTing cluster data. This cluster's normal baseline differs slightly \u2014 live calibration showed normal pods score \u2248 0.05\u20130.06. Threshold is set to 0.08 to avoid constant false positives; genuine attacks (e.g. mass `clone` calls, large VAE error) score \u2265 0.10.\n\n**Why the IF score is negative for normal pods:** sklearn's `decision_function` returns **positive** for normal samples (long path through trees = not easily isolated) and **negative** for anomalies (short path = isolated quickly). We negate it so that *higher always means more anomalous*. A healthy pod shows IF \u2248 \u22120.10 (normal); an attacking pod shows IF > 0 (anomalous).\n\n> **Quick investigation guide:** High consecutive attacks \u2192 sustained, not a false positive. Check **Last Attack Trace \u2192 Top Syscalls** for behavioural evidence (e.g. `mmap\u00d71000` = memory abuse \u00b7 `connect\u00d7100` = port scan \u00b7 `openat\u00d750` = file snooping)."
          },
          "fieldConfig": {
            "defaults": {},
            "overrides": []
          },
          "transparent": true
        },
        {
          "id": 101,
          "type": "text",
          "title": "",
          "gridPos": {
            "y": 8,
            "x": 0,
            "h": 6,
            "w": 24
          },
          "options": {
            "mode": "markdown",
            "content": "| Panel | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| **Total Attack Events** | Cumulative attack-classified traces since detector start. Resets on restart. Filter by Pod (top of page) to see per-pod totals. |\n| **Pods in Stream** | Pods sending syscall events via Tetragon. Appears immediately on first event \u2014 before any scoring. |\n| **Pods Scored** | Pods with at least one completed process trace scored. Lower than \"in stream\" if some processes haven't exited yet. |\n| **Detection Threshold** | Ensemble score cut-off: score \u2265 threshold \u2192 ATTACK. Raise to reduce false positives; lower to catch more attacks. |\n| **p95 Latency** | 95th-percentile time to score one trace (featurize + IF + VAE). Under 50 ms is healthy for the current event rate. |"
          },
          "fieldConfig": {
            "defaults": {},
            "overrides": []
          },
          "transparent": true
        },
        {
          "id": 102,
          "type": "text",
          "title": "",
          "gridPos": {
            "y": 15,
            "x": 0,
            "h": 3,
            "w": 24
          },
          "options": {
            "mode": "markdown",
            "content": "Each data point represents one **completed process trace**. The **dashed orange line** is the detection threshold \u2014 traces above it are classified as attacks. Score = `0.7 \u00d7 VAE_scaled + 0.3 \u00d7 IF_scaled`. After scaling, the centre of normal behaviour is near 0; attack traces score higher. Spikes near or above the threshold line are worth investigating \u2014 check **Last Attack Trace** for the syscall breakdown."
          },
          "fieldConfig": {
            "defaults": {},
            "overrides": []
          },
          "transparent": true
        },
        {
          "id": 103,
          "type": "text",
          "title": "",
          "gridPos": {
            "y": 22,
            "x": 0,
            "h": 5,
            "w": 24
          },
          "options": {
            "mode": "markdown",
            "content": "| Panel | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| **Attack Rate %** | Percentage of the last 20 scored traces classified as attacks. Near 100% = pod is *consistently* anomalous, not a one-off spike. |\n| **Consecutive Attack Windows** | Back-to-back attack traces with no normal trace in between. Resets to 0 on the first normal trace. A large count is the strongest attack signal \u2014 sustained anomaly across multiple process executions. |"
          },
          "fieldConfig": {
            "defaults": {},
            "overrides": []
          },
          "transparent": true
        },
        {
          "id": 104,
          "type": "text",
          "title": "",
          "gridPos": {
            "y": 29,
            "x": 0,
            "h": 6,
            "w": 24
          },
          "options": {
            "mode": "markdown",
            "content": "**Why the Isolation Forest score is negative for normal pods:**\nsklearn's `decision_function` returns **positive** for normal samples (long path = many splits needed = not easily isolated) and **negative** for anomalies (short path = isolated quickly). We negate it so higher always means more anomalous. Normal pods show IF \u2248 \u22120.10; attacking pods show IF > 0.\n\n**Compare the two models to understand *why* a trace was flagged:**\n- **VAE high + IF low (negative)** \u2192 unusual syscall *sequence* (call order / bigrams atypical, e.g. unexpected execve after socket)\n- **IF high (positive) + VAE low** \u2192 unusual syscall *frequency* (one call dominates far more than normal, e.g. mmap \u00d71000)\n- **Both high** \u2192 strongest attack signal \u2014 both frequency and sequence are anomalous"
          },
          "fieldConfig": {
            "defaults": {},
            "overrides": []
          },
          "transparent": true
        },
        {
          "id": 105,
          "type": "text",
          "title": "",
          "gridPos": {
            "y": 36,
            "x": 0,
            "h": 5,
            "w": 24
          },
          "options": {
            "mode": "markdown",
            "content": "| Panel | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| **Windows Scored / min** | Completed process traces scored per minute. Cryptominers score many windows because they spawn many short-lived worker processes. Normal apps score fewer because their processes are longer-lived. |\n| **Inference Latency** | p50 / p95 / p99 scoring time per trace. Spikes in p99 indicate long traces (many syscalls \u2192 more featurization work) or CPU contention on the host. Under 50 ms p95 is healthy. |"
          },
          "fieldConfig": {
            "defaults": {},
            "overrides": []
          },
          "transparent": true
        }
      ],
      "datasource": null,
      "targets": []
    },
